{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17415630","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17415630"},"attributes":{"position":57,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T09:11:57+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T09:11:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261100"}},"session":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261100"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11979"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17512913","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17512913"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:03:11+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:03:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11979"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261100","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionSessions/1261100"},"attributes":{"startedAt":"2025-09-28T07:52:04+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-28T10:28:52+09:30","sessionType":"qbank","questionStatus":"all","difficulty":[],"timeLimit":null,"questionCount":62,"questionsAnswered":61,"marksTotal":61,"marksAttainable":61,"marksAttempted":61,"finishedAt":"2025-09-28T09:15:31+09:30","resultsAvailable":true,"score":0.2,"questionsCorrect":12,"marksCorrect":12},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"pack":{"data":{"type":"packs","id":"5"}},"exam":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questions","id":"11979","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11979"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.77,0.03,0.1,0.07,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4569"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48887"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4569","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4569"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11979"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33885"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"483"},{"type":"tags","id":"2534"},{"type":"tags","id":"3406"},{"type":"tags","id":"4061"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6849"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6901"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12286"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48887","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/48887"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 41-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a two-day history of jaundice. He has a medical history of hypertension. He also has a four-year history of progressive shortness of breath on exertion and occasional wheezing which he has not had investigated. His only regular medication is enalapril. He reports drinking two standard drinks per day, does not smoke and has never used recreational drugs. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 72/min, blood pressure 120/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Jaundice and scleral icterus are noted. Cardiorespiratory examination reveals occasional wheezing on expiration and normal heart sounds. Abdominal examination is unremarkable. Investigations show:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETotal bilirubin: 65 \u03bcmol/L (3-20)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EConjugated bilirubin: 40 \u03bcmol/L (0-5)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EALT: 120 U/L (5-40)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAST: 90 U/L (5-40)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EALP: 150 U/L (30-120)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGGT: 180 U/L (5-60).\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EChest X-ray shows hyperinflated lung fields with flattened diaphragms.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely explanation for this patient\u0027s presentation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["\u03b11-antitrypsin deficiency","Wilson\u0027s disease","Primary sclerosing cholangitis","Alcoholic liver disease","Haemochromatosis"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s presentation is most consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003E\u03b11-antitrypsin deficiency\u003C/strong\u003E (AATD). The combination of early-onset respiratory symptoms suggestive of chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD), along with signs of liver disease, strongly suggests this genetic condition. The chest X-ray findings of hyperinflated lung fields with flattened diaphragms are consistent with COPD. AATD affects the lungs, liver, and occasionally the skin. The liver involvement in AATD is due to the accumulation of mutant \u03b11-antitrypsin in hepatocytes, leading to hepatocyte injury and eventually cirrhosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWilson\u0027s disease\u003C/strong\u003E is a genetic disorder of copper metabolism that can cause liver disease and neurological symptoms. While it can present with jaundice and elevated liver enzymes, it typically affects younger individuals (often in their teens or early twenties) and is not associated with respiratory symptoms or COPD. Neurological symptoms such as tremors or psychiatric disturbances are common in Wilson\u0027s disease but are not present in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrimary sclerosing cholangitis\u003C/strong\u003E (PSC) is a chronic liver disease characterized by inflammation and fibrosis of the bile ducts. While it can cause jaundice and elevated liver enzymes, it is not typically associated with respiratory symptoms or COPD. PSC is more common in young to middle-aged men and is often associated with inflammatory bowel disease, which is not mentioned in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlcoholic liver disease\u003C/strong\u003E could be considered given the patient\u0027s daily alcohol consumption. However, the reported intake of two standard drinks per day is relatively modest and unlikely to cause significant liver damage in most individuals. Moreover, alcoholic liver disease does not explain the respiratory symptoms and COPD-like changes on chest X-ray.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHaemochromatosis\u003C/strong\u003E is a genetic disorder of iron overload that can cause liver disease. However, it is not associated with respiratory symptoms or COPD, and may instead present with fatigue, joint pain, and skin pigmentation changes, which are not mentioned in this case.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Severe \u03b11-antitrypsin deficiency is a well-known risk factor for developing chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD) and liver disease.","Pathogenesis of \u03b11-antrypsin deficiency in liver disease is due to the accumulation of \u03b11-antitrypsin (AAT) in the rough endoplasmic reticulum through a mechanism of polymerization."],"references":["Tanash HA, Piitulainen E. Liver disease in adults with severe alpha-1-antitrypsin deficiency. J Gastroenterol. 2019;54(6):541-548. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6536463/."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33885"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11979"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33885","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/33885"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-07-19T12:53:55+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-07-19T12:53:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4569"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48887"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relatio